<head>

<title>SET-EXTREME-OPINION</title>
</head>

<body>

	<h3><i>I initialise the uncertainty with which I hold an opinion.</i> </h3>
	<font size="2" color="gray">Begin micro-behaviour</font>
	<p><b>SET-EXTREME-OPINION</b></p>
	<font size="2" color="gray">Begin NetLogo code:</font>
	<pre>substitute-text-area-for initial-opinion random-item [-1 1]
substitute-text-area-for initial-uncertainty 0.1          
set my-opinion initial-opinion
set my-uncertainty initial-uncertainty
</pre>
	<font size="2" color="gray">End NetLogo code</font>
	<h2>Variants</h2>
	<p>You can initialise the <i>my-opinion</i> attribute to any value. You can 
	also a different uncertainty value instead of 0.1 or use a random number 
	instead.</p>
	<h2>Related Micro-behaviours</h2>

	<p>These attributes are used by
	<a title="RELATIVE-AGREEMENT" href="RELATIVE-AGREEMENT.html">RELATIVE-AGREEMENT</a>.
	<a title="SET-RANDOM-OPINION" href="SET-RANDOM-OPINION.html">SET-RANDOM-OPINION</a> 
	and <a title="SET-OPINION-UNCERTAINITY" href="SET-OPINION-UNCERTAINTY.html">
	SET-OPINION-UNCERTAINTY</a> to create a population with a variety of 
	opinions.</p>
	<h2>How this works</h2>
	<p>It sets the attribute <i>my-opinion</i> to either -1 or 1 with equal 
	probability and sets <i>my-uncertainty</i> to a 0.1 as was done in the model 
	described in [1].</p>
	<h2>History</h2>


	<p>This was implemented by Ken Kahn.</p>
	<h2><span class="mw-headline">Footnotes </span></h2>
	<p>[1] An implementation of &quot;How can extremism prevail? A study based on the 
	relative agreement interaction model&quot; by Guillaume Deffuant, Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric 
	Amblard, G&eacute;rard Weisbuch and Thierry Faure (2002); Journal of Artificial 
	Societies and Social Simulation vol. 5, no. 4; &lt;<a class="external free" title="http://jasss.soc.surrey.ac.uk/5/4/1.html#2.3" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://jasss.soc.surrey.ac.uk/5/4/1.html#2.3">http://jasss.soc.surrey.ac.uk/5/4/1.html#2.3</a>&gt;
</p>

